{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c18ee33d-9418-49ee-b14f-e6337b52bd83","content":"I can help guide you through analyzing the dump, but note that the tools available in this environment are focused on **collecting** dumps rather than analyzing them.\n\nFor analyzing a `.dmp` file, here are your best options:\n\n### `dotnet-dump analyze` (cross-platform)\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\ndotnet-dump analyze <your-file.dmp>\n```\nUseful commands inside the analyzer:\n- **`clrstack`** — managed call stack of the crashing thread\n- **`pe` (PrintException)** — show the last exception\n- **`dumpheap -stat`** — heap summary (for OOM crashes)\n- **`threads`** — list all managed threads\n- **`setthread <id>`** then `clrstack` — inspect other threads\n\n### WinDbg + SOS (Windows, richest experience)\n```\n.loadby sos coreclr\n!PrintException\n!ClrStack\n!Threads\n```\n\n### Quick triage flow\n1. Run `pe` / `PrintException` first — most crashes have an unhandled exception.\n2. Run `clrstack` to see where it happened.\n3. If it's a `StackOverflowException` or `OutOfMemoryException`, use `dumpheap -stat` or `threads` for deeper analysis.\n\nWould you like me to install `dotnet-dump` in this environment and walk you through the analysis? If so, upload or provide the path to your `.dmp` file.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4b3880aa-5b18-4459-b1db-d914db226286","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user has a .dmp crash dump file from a .NET application and wants to analyze it to find the root cause of the crash. Let me help them with this.\n\nLooking at the available skills, I see there's a `dump-collect` skill, but its description says it's for **collecting** crash dumps, NOT for analyzing them. It explicitly says \"DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze.\"\n\nSo I shouldn't use that skill. Let me help them directly with guidance on analyzing the dump file.\n\nI should provide guidance on how to analyze the dump. The main tools for .NET dump analysis are:\n\n\n1. `dotnet-dump analyze` - cross-platform managed dump analysis\n2. WinDbg (Windows) with SOS extension\n3. lldb with SOS plugin (Linux/macOS)\n\nSince we're on Linux, `dotnet-dump analyze` would be the most straightforward approach. I should ask where the dump file is located and whether they want me to walk them through using dotnet-dump to investigate the crash.","outputTokens":641,"requestId":"CB04:9C8D1:729B46:83A330:6A052B21"},"id":"eff2b485-9b2f-4d96-ad68-04e43cf69790","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:53:52.562Z","parentId":"7ebdfd38-5fb5-48ec-9b8b-1909d912d83c"}
